@NODE "ed" "The Prefs Editor"
@PREV "usage"
@TOC "MAIN"
@{B}The Prefs Editor@{UB}

This program is used to enter the prefs for your ISPs and 'phone company, Miami paths and some other
stuff.  It is split into three main pages, Coster, ISP and Misc.

@{"Coster" LINK "coster"}
@{"ISP" LINK "isp"}
@{"Misc" LINK "misc"}

@ENDNODE

@NODE "prog" "NetLink Program"
@PREV "usage"
@TOC "MAIN"
@{B}NetLink Program@{UB}

Simple.  You have two buttons.  Online.  Offline.  They do that.  To the right of these is the
current system time, unless you have "Show Time" selected when this will become the online time, when
online.

Underneath there is the lamp and text gadgets both showing a report of what is going on.
The call costs are shown in the text gadget.

Thats it.

NB:
Please turn off any rexx scripts that control Miami.  NetLink does not check Miami as it used to do,
so best to turn them all off.  Also if Miami is some how quit NetLink will wait till you load it
again manually, I did have auto load  but it felt a bit wierd.  If you want auto load/quit then ensure
"auto isp" is on (it works now).  Although I don't like myself.  You will lose all data if you quit
Miami whilst NetLink is running.  You will also have to load Miami to be able to quit from NetLink,
so best not mess!!!



@ENDNODE

@NODE "coster" "Coster"
@PREV "usage"
@TOC "MAIN"
@{B}Coster Page@{UB}

This page shows all the phone details required by NetLink to calculate the cost of the call.
The list shows the current "rates" avaliable.  A rate is the name I use to describe a period of time
within which a constant charge is made per second/minute.

To create a rate, simply click create rate, select the new entry, edit the name, edit the start and
finish times for that rate using the respective sliders,
and then using 0 = Sunday 1 = Monday 2 = Tuesday etc . . system enter
which days of the week that rate is valid in the "Active On" gadget for example if a rate is only
valid at weekends then use "06" ( Sunday Saturday ) or if you wanted Monday, Wednesday and Friday you
would use, "135".  You can stick any "blank space" character inbetween the values, such as commas,
spaces and underscores so "135" is the same as "1 3 5" or "1,3,5". Then enter the price for the rate
in the "Rate Price" gadget.  This value should be in the same denomination that you wish the output
to be in, for example if I wanted to know the call cost in pounds then I would need to put the value
in "Rate Price" in pounds, 0.10 for 10 pence.

The gadgets at the bottom of this page are global in that they apply to all the rates defined.  These
being the character you wish to see infront of the output cost.  The minimum charge, if any your
'phone company charges. Also remember to set the method of charging, either per minute or per second,
this can have alarming results if you don't set this right!!!!

NB:
You may define up to 50 rates after that NetLink does not look at them.  I think 50 is loads though, I
only use three.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "isp" "ISP"
@PREV "usage"
@TOC "MAIN"
@{B}ISP Page@{UB}

This page is where you will see your ISP data availiable.  I suggest that you go to the Misc page
first, then save the prefs and re-start NetLinkPrefs, if you do not see any file name in the list.

Creating an ISP file.  These are just Miami config files, with any name but ending in ".isp" simple.
So go into Miami and create a new profile of an ISP and save it as myisp.isp or something and when
you start NetLinkPrefs it will be availiable.  You must save and re-start NetLinkPrefs each time you
create an ISP in Miami, as I have not figured out a way of reading dirs dynamically (yet).

Ok so you have a few ISPs avaliable to you so click on one and the bottom gadgets should enable.

ISP Active, if not ticked this ISP will NOT be used EVER.
During, here you should type or use the PopList to chose one or more of your pre-defined rates,
        within which you want this ISP to be used.
ISP Priority, set this what you want, it is the priority NetLink uses to determine the ISP to use
               in a conflict, i.e. more than one ISP for a single rate.

ISP Check Ping and Ping rate are not used but will be.

@ENDNODE

